In [183]:
#The below graph is a depiction of the seven day moving average of new cases of COVID-19 for the period between 
#Jan 20 – Mar 22 in the USA. The new cases were grouped by day and summed. The chart shows the US Daily New Cases in light 
#grey, with the smoothed 7-day rolling average in red. The COVID-19 trend in the US is depicted very well in this chart. 
#The viewer can see that there were very few new cases in Jan 2020, then we can see the first peak in July 2020 which is 
#around the time that summer fun was ending. Fall to winter of 2020 saw a triple top peak, which was around the time that 
#many Americans were through with the lockdowns and chose enjoying the Holidays over safety. There was a steep drop-off in 
#Spring 2021 when the vaccine became available, but another huge peak in Sep-Oct 2021 when schools were back in session. 
#his was followed by a drop-off, then record setting new cases with the onset of the Omicron variant. We then see a steep 
#drop off as many citizens got first time and booster vaccines.
In [182]:
